TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Nontraditional Quality of Organizational Learning
AU  - Weick, Karl E.
Y1  - 1991/02/01
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/orsc.2.1.116
DO  - 10.1287/orsc.2.1.116
T2  - Organization Science
JF  - Organization Science
JO  - Organization Science
SP  - 116
EP  - 124
VL  - 2
IS  - 1
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - The traditional definition of learning as a shift in performance when the stimulus situation remains essentially the same implies a set of conditions that occur rarely in organizations. Thus, either organizational learning is an infrequent event, or it occurs frequently but takes a nontraditional form. Both possibilities are reviewed and implications for research strategy are suggested.
AB  - The traditional definition of learning as a shift in performance when the stimulus situation remains essentially the same implies a set of conditions that occur rarely in organizations. Thus, either organizational learning is an infrequent event, or it occurs frequently but takes a nontraditional form. Both possibilities are reviewed and implications for research strategy are suggested.
